The US Supreme Court recently debated the legality of the death penalty for criminals under 18, focusing on the case of Christopher Simmons.
Advocates argued against executing juvenile offenders, drawing parallels to the ban on executing the mentally ill.
Justices grappled with the moral implications of executing young murderers, considering a potential shift in national consensus.
The court also addressed the issue of federal sentencing guidelines following the Blakely ruling.
The debate extended to the use of marijuana for medicinal purposes, questioning Congress's authority to regulate intrastate drug use.
Overall, the court's decisions may reflect evolving societal attitudes towards juvenile justice and criminal sentencing.
